{"type":"simple","docs":[{"id":"/architecture/overview","title":"Architecture Overview","description":"High-level architecture of the Orion Password Manager ecosystem — a zero-knowledge, decentralized credential manager built on Sui.","url":"/architecture/overview","content":"Architecture Overview\nOrion is a zero-knowledge, decentralized password manager that combines the security of client-side AES-256-GCM encryption with the permanence of on-chain storage on Sui and Walrus. Users authenticate via zkLogin (Google OAuth), eliminating the need for seed phrases or wallets.\n  Orion was designed and built for the CommandOSS Hackathon by Mysten Labs — leveraging 100% native Sui technologies.\n System Components\nThe ecosystem consists of four deployable units:\n Component  Technology  Purpose \n---------\n Extension  React + TypeScript + Vite (Manifest V3)  User-facing browser extension with popup UI, content scripts, and background service worker \n Smart Contract  Sui Move  On-chain vault pointer () with versioned rotation and event emission \n Gas Station  Node.js (Express)  Sponsored transaction relay — users never pay gas fees \n Landing  Vite + React  Marketing page and public documentation \n High-Level Data Flow\n Zero-Knowledge Encryption Model\nOrion follows a two-layer key hierarchy inspired by industry standards like 1Password and Bitwarden:\n1. DEK (Data Encryption Key): A random 256-bit key generated once per vault. It encrypts all credential data.\n2. KEK (Key Encryption Key): Derived from the user's Master PIN via Argon2id. It wraps (encrypts) the DEK.\n3. Recovery KEK: Derived from a one-time Recovery Code. It wraps the same DEK, providing an independent recovery path.\n  The Master PIN and Recovery Code are never stored anywhere — not in the extension, not on the blockchain, not on Walrus. If both are lost, the vault is cryptographically irrecoverable.\n Vault Synchronization Pipeline\nEvery CRUD operation (Add / Edit / Delete credential) triggers an atomic, serialized sync pipeline:\n Step 1: Local Mutation\nThe credential is encrypted with the DEK and saved to Chrome's  storage (RAM-only).\n Step 2: Encrypt & Package\nThe full vault is re-encrypted with the DEK. The DEK itself is re-wrapped with the KEK. Both are bundled into a .\n Step 3: Upload to Walrus\nThe encrypted payload is uploaded as a binary blob to the Walrus Publisher endpoint, returning a .\n Step 4: Update On-Chain Pointer\nA  to  updates the  object with the new . This transaction is sponsored (zero gas for users) and signed with a zkLogin signature.\n Step 5: Offline Cache\nThe encrypted payload and latest  are cached in  for instant offline recovery.\n Technology Stack\n Layer  Technology  Why \n---------\n Authentication  zkLogin (Enoki)  Web2-grade UX — sign in with Google, no seed phrases \n Key Derivation  Argon2id (hash-wasm)  Memory-hard KDF resistant to GPU/ASIC brute-force attacks \n Encryption  AES-256-GCM (Web Crypto API)  Authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD) \n Decentralized Storage  Walrus Protocol  Content-addressed, immutable blob storage on Sui \n On-Chain State  Sui Move (EncryptedVaultKey)  Versioned pointer to the latest Walrus blob, owned by the user's zkLogin address \n Gas Sponsorship  Enoki Sponsored Transactions  Users never need SUI tokens to interact with the blockchain \n Extension Runtime  Chrome Manifest V3  Service worker-based background, Shadow DOM content scripts"},{"id":"/architecture/security-model","title":"Security Model","description":"Threat model, cryptographic design, and defense-in-depth strategy for the Orion Password Manager.","url":"/architecture/security-model","content":"Security Model\nOrion implements a defense-in-depth security architecture. Every layer — from user input to blockchain finality — is designed to ensure that no single point of compromise can expose plaintext credentials.\n Threat Model\n Threat  Mitigation \n------\n Compromised local storage  All data at rest is AES-256-GCM encrypted. The DEK is never stored in plaintext — only wrapped by the KEK (derived from the Master PIN). \n Brute-force Master PIN  Argon2id with 15 iterations and 64MB memory makes each guess take 500ms, even on modern hardware. \n Man-in-the-middle (Walrus)  All data uploaded to Walrus is already encrypted client-side. Walrus only ever sees ciphertext. \n Malicious content script injection  The autofill UI uses Shadow DOM isolation. CSS/JS on the host page cannot read or tamper with Orion's injected UI. \n Phishing via similar domains  Domain matching uses strict hostname comparison —  will never match credentials saved for . \n Session hijacking  Sensitive session data (DEK, PIN, zkLogin JWT) is stored in  (RAM-only) and auto-expires via a configurable timeout. \n Replay attacks on-chain  Each  has a monotonically incrementing  field. Stale updates are detectable. \n Race conditions during sync  The background service worker uses a serial queue ( chaining) to prevent concurrent Walrus/Sui updates. \n Cryptographic Primitives\n Key Derivation — Argon2id\n  Argon2id is the winner of the Password Hashing Competition (PHC) and is recommended by OWASP for password storage. It combines Argon2i's resistance to side-channel attacks with Argon2d's resistance to GPU cracking.\n Encryption — AES-256-GCM\nEvery encryption operation generates:\n- A fresh 16-byte random salt (for KDF-based encryption) or uses a raw key (for DEK-based encryption)\n- A fresh 12-byte random IV (initialization vector)\n- A ciphertext with integrated authentication tag (GCM mode)\n Vault Payload Structure\nThe complete encrypted payload stored on Walrus:\n Session Security\nOrion uses Chrome's session storage () which exists only in RAM and is automatically cleared when the browser closes.\n Stored in Session (RAM-only)\n Key  Purpose  Auto-cleared? \n---------\n   Master PIN hash  ✅ On timeout or browser close \n   Derived KEK material  ✅ On timeout or browser close \n   Data Encryption Key  ✅ On timeout or browser close \n   Decrypted vault entries  ✅ On timeout or browser close \n   Google OAuth JWT  ✅ On timeout or browser close \n Stored in Local Storage (Encrypted)\n Key  Purpose  Encryption \n---------\n   Offline vault cache  AES-256-GCM (DEK) \n   JWT + zkState + zkProof  AES-256-GCM (KEK) \n   Sui object reference  None (non-sensitive) \n   User's zkLogin address  None (public data) \n Auto-Lock Timeout\nUsers can configure session timeout from the extension settings:\n Option  Duration  Use Case \n---------\n Maximum Security  1 minute  Public/shared computers \n Balanced  15 minutes  Default — recommended \n Standard  1 hour  Personal workstations \n Never  ∞  Trusted devices only \nThe background service worker runs a 10-second polling interval to check and enforce session expiry.\n Domain Matching (Anti-Phishing)\nThe autofill engine uses strict hostname matching to prevent phishing attacks:\nThis means:\n- ✅  matches credentials saved for \n- ✅  matches credentials saved for  (subdomain)\n- ❌  does NOT match\n- ❌  does NOT match\n Sync Concurrency Control\nTo prevent race conditions when multiple CRUD operations fire in rapid succession, the background service worker implements a serial queue:\nThis guarantees that each sync operation completes fully (Walrus upload + Sui update) before the next one begins, preventing data loss or version conflicts on-chain.\n Recovery System\nThe Emergency Kit recovery system provides a safe escape hatch when the Master PIN is forgotten:\n Step 1: Generate Recovery Code\nDuring vault initialization, a one-time Recovery Code is generated. The DEK is encrypted with both the Master KEK and the Recovery KEK.\n Step 2: Store Both Wrappers\nBoth  (KEK-wrapped) and  (Recovery KEK-wrapped) are stored together in the Walrus blob.\n Step 3: Recovery Flow\nThe user provides the Recovery Code. The system fetches the latest  from Sui, downloads the blob from Walrus, decrypts the DEK using the Recovery KEK, and re-wraps it with a new Master KEK.\n  The Recovery Code is shown once during initialization. It is never stored by Orion. Users must save it offline (printed paper, hardware vault, etc.)."},{"id":"/architecture/authentication","title":"Authentication Flow","description":"Complete zkLogin authentication flow — from Google OAuth to Sui address derivation.","url":"/architecture/authentication","content":"Authentication Flow\nOrion uses Sui zkLogin (via Mysten's Enoki service) to provide a seamless Web2 login experience. Users sign in with their Google account and receive a deterministic Sui address — no wallets, no seed phrases.\n Flow Diagram\n Technical Details\n 1. Ephemeral Keypair Generation\nEach login session generates a fresh Ed25519 keypair that is valid for  (current epoch + 30 ≈ 30 days):\n 2. Google OAuth via Chrome Identity API\nThe background worker uses  for a native OAuth experience:\n 3. Sui Address Derivation (Enoki)\nThe JWT is sent to Enoki to deterministically derive a Sui address:\n  The same Google account always produces the same Sui address — this is deterministic and managed by Enoki's salt service.\n 4. zkProof Generation\nWhen the user initializes or unlocks their vault, a zero-knowledge proof is generated:\nThis proof allows blockchain transactions to be signed without revealing the user's Google identity on-chain.\n 5. Credential Persistence\nTo avoid re-authenticating with Google on every browser restart, the JWT, zkState, and zkProof are encrypted with the user's KEK and stored locally:\nOn unlock, these credentials are decrypted with the Master PIN, restoring the full session without any network calls to Google or Enoki.\n Post-Login States\nAfter successful login, the extension determines the user's vault state:\n State  Condition  Next Screen \n---------\n New User  No  on-chain  Create Vault (set Master PIN + Recovery Code) \n Returning User   exists  Unlock Vault (enter Master PIN)"},{"id":"/contract/overview","title":"Smart Contract Overview","description":"Sui Move smart contract for the Orion Password Manager — on-chain vault pointers with versioned rotation.","url":"/contract/overview","content":"Smart Contract\nThe Orion smart contract is written in Sui Move and deployed on Sui Testnet. It serves as the trust anchor of the entire system — a tamper-proof, user-owned pointer to the latest encrypted vault blob on Walrus.\n  Package ID:   \n  Module:   \n  Network: Sui Testnet\n Why On-Chain?\nUnlike centralized password managers (LastPass, Chrome Passwords), Orion's on-chain pointer guarantees:\n1. User Ownership: The  is an owned object — only the user's zkLogin address can modify it.\n2. Immutable Audit Trail: Every rotation emits an event, creating a permanent history on the Sui blockchain.\n3. Censorship Resistance: No centralized party can lock the user out of their vault pointer.\n4. Cross-Device Discovery: Any device can discover the user's vault by querying their Sui address.\n Contract Structure\nThe contract consists of a single module with two core functions:\n Data Model\n EncryptedVaultKey\nThe primary on-chain object — acts as a pointer to the encrypted vault on Walrus:\n Field  Type  Purpose \n---------\n     Unique Sui object identifier \n     UTF-8 encoded Walrus blob ID (content-addressed hash) \n     Monotonically incrementing counter, starts at 1 \n     The Sui epoch when the vault was first created \n  The  stores the reference to encrypted data, not the data itself. The actual encrypted vault lives on Walrus. Even if someone reads this on-chain, they only get an opaque blob ID — the content is AES-256-GCM encrypted and cryptographically useless without the user's Master PIN.\n Events\nTwo events provide a full audit trail:\n Core Functions\n  — Create a New Vault Pointer\nCalled once per user during vault initialization. Creates a new  and transfers it to the sender.\nSecurity properties:\n- ✅ Validates  is non-empty\n- ✅ Object is transferred to  (the user's zkLogin address)\n- ✅ Emits  for indexing and audit\n  — Rotate the Vault Pointer\nCalled on every sync operation. Updates the  to point to the latest encrypted blob.\nSecurity properties:\n- ✅ Requires  — only the owner can provide this reference (enforced by Sui's object model)\n- ✅ Version is monotonically incremented — prevents rollback attacks\n- ✅ Emits  with the new version number\n Object Discovery\nThe extension discovers the user's vault by querying owned objects filtered by struct type:\nIf multiple  objects exist (edge case from failed past operations), the parser selects the one with the highest version number.\n Transaction Execution\nAll on-chain transactions use zkLogin + Sponsored Transactions:\n  Users never need SUI tokens. All gas fees are covered by the project's Gas Station via Enoki's Sponsored Transaction API."},{"id":"/contract/recovery-module","title":"Recovery Module","description":"Emergency Kit recovery system — vault restoration when the Master PIN is forgotten.","url":"/contract/recovery-module","content":"Recovery Module\nThe Recovery Module provides a decentralized escape hatch for users who lose their Master PIN. Unlike centralized password managers where a company can reset your account, Orion's recovery is entirely self-sovereign — only the user holding the Recovery Code can restore access.\n How It Works\n Data Structure\nThe  stored on Walrus always contains both key wrappers:\n Recovery Flow (Step by Step)\n Step 1: Fetch Vault Pointer from Sui\nThe system queries the Sui blockchain directly to find the user's latest , regardless of local storage state:\n Step 2: Download Encrypted Payload from Walrus\n Step 3: Decrypt DEK with Recovery Code\nThe Recovery Code is used to derive a Recovery KEK, which decrypts the  field:\n  If the Recovery Code is incorrect,  will throw an  (AES-GCM authentication failure). The system catches this and returns .\n Step 4: Re-encrypt with New Master PIN\nThe recovered DEK is re-wrapped with a new Master KEK derived from the user's new Master PIN:\n Step 5: Update Local Credentials\nThe encrypted zkLogin credentials are also re-encrypted with the new KEK:\n Recovery Code Generation\nThe Recovery Code is generated during vault initialization only. It is a user-provided string (minimum 8 characters) that is:\n1. Combined with the user's Sui address: \n2. Used as input to Argon2id to derive a Recovery KEK\n3. Used to encrypt the DEK into the  field\n  The Recovery Code is address-bound — the same code used with a different Google account produces a completely different KEK, making it useless for cross-account attacks.\n Backward Compatibility\nVaults created before the Recovery feature was added will not have a  field. The system handles this gracefully:\n Recovery Code Preservation During Sync\nWhen the vault is synced (after any CRUD operation), the system preserves the existing  from the previous payload:\nThis ensures the Recovery Code remains valid across all sync operations without requiring the user to re-enter it."},{"id":"/contract/gas-station","title":"Gas Station","description":"Sponsored transaction relay — enabling gasless interactions for all Orion users.","url":"/contract/gas-station","content":"Gas Station\nThe Orion Gas Station is a lightweight Node.js server that sponsors all blockchain transactions for Orion users. This means users never need to hold SUI tokens — the project covers all gas fees via Mysten's Enoki Sponsored Transaction API.\n Why Sponsored Transactions?\nFor a password manager to achieve mainstream adoption, users cannot be expected to:\n- Understand gas fees\n- Acquire SUI tokens from an exchange\n- Manage a separate crypto wallet\nSponsored transactions eliminate this friction entirely.\n Architecture\n API Endpoints\n \nCreates a sponsored transaction.\nRequest:\nResponse:\n \nExecutes a previously sponsored transaction with the user's zkLogin signature.\nRequest:\nResponse:\n Extension Integration\nThe  class handles the client-side assembly:\n  The Gas Station server is configured to run on . For production deployment, it should be placed behind HTTPS with rate limiting."},{"id":"/extension/overview","title":"Extension Overview","description":"Orion Browser Extension — Manifest V3 architecture, component structure, and messaging system.","url":"/extension/overview","content":"Extension Overview\nThe Orion Extension is a Chrome Manifest V3 browser extension built with React, TypeScript, and Vite. It is the primary user interface for managing the encrypted vault.\n Project Structure\n Architecture Layers\n Messaging System\nAll communication between the popup UI and the background service worker uses a typed message dispatch system:\nThe  class in the background worker provides a chainable registration API:\n Application State Machine\nThe  component manages the top-level application state:\n Content Script (Autofill Engine)\nThe  module is injected into all web pages and provides:\n1. Field Detection: Scans for  and adjacent username fields\n2. Domain Matching: Queries the background for credentials matching the current hostname\n3. Shadow DOM UI: Injects a premium autofill bar below the password field, completely isolated from the host page's CSS\nThe autofill bar features:\n- Emerald-and-black signature glass theme\n- Animated dropdown with avatar initials\n- One-click fill with success animation feedback\n- Multiple account support\n Configuration\nAll configuration is centralized in :"},{"id":"/extension/background","title":"Background Service Worker","description":"The Orion Secrets Engine — message handling, vault sync, and blockchain interactions.","url":"/extension/background","content":"Background Service Worker\nThe  module is the Secrets Engine of Orion. It runs as a Manifest V3 service worker and acts as the single source of truth for all sensitive operations.\n Responsibilities\n Domain  Operations \n------\n Session  Set, get, extend, clear session (PIN + KEK + DEK) \n Vault CRUD  Save, update, delete encrypted credentials \n Sync  Encrypt vault → Upload to Walrus → Update Sui pointer \n Autofill  Decrypt credentials and send to content scripts \n Auth  Orchestrate Google OAuth + zkLogin flow \n Recovery  Master PIN change and Emergency Kit recovery \n Serial Sync Queue\nThe most critical architectural decision in the background worker is the serial sync queue:\nThis prevents race conditions when users rapidly add/edit/delete credentials. Without this queue, concurrent Walrus uploads could result in the Sui pointer referencing a stale blob.\n Sync Pipeline Detail\n Message Handlers\n Session Management\n Message  Handler  Description \n---------\n     Creates a new vault session \n     Returns current session or null \n     Extends session expiry \n     Wipes all session data from RAM \n Vault Operations\n Message  Handler  Description \n---------\n     Returns decrypted vault from session RAM \n   Encrypt password with DEK, save to session  Adds a new credential \n   Re-encrypt if password changed, update session  Edits a credential \n     Removes a credential \n     Full sync pipeline \n Autofill\n Message  Handler  Description \n---------\n   Filter vault by hostname  Returns matching credential metadata \n   Decrypt + send FILLFIELDS to active tab  Popup-triggered autofill \n   Decrypt by credential ID  Content script autofill \n   Decrypt password for display  Password reveal in UI \n Security Operations\n Message  Handler  Description \n---------\n   OAuth + zkLogin flow  Returns  \n   Re-encrypt credentials + trigger sync  Master PIN change \n   Fetch from Sui → decrypt with Recovery → re-wrap  Emergency recovery \n Session Manager\nThe  class manages vault session lifecycle using Chrome's  storage (RAM-only):\n   is automatically wiped when the browser process exits. This means closing Chrome immediately locks the vault — no sensitive data survives in local storage."},{"id":"/extension/crypto-engine","title":"Crypto Engine","description":"Deep dive into Orion's client-side cryptography — AES-256-GCM, Argon2id, DEK/KEK hierarchy.","url":"/extension/crypto-engine","content":"Crypto Engine\nThe  class () is the cryptographic core of Orion. All encryption and decryption happens exclusively on the client — the background service worker and Walrus only ever handle ciphertext.\n Key Hierarchy\n API Reference\n \nEncrypts data using a password-derived key (Argon2id → AES-256-GCM).\nUsed for: Wrapping the DEK with a KEK.\n Parameter  Type  Description \n---------\n     Data to encrypt \n     Password material for KDF \n Returns     \nInternal flow:\n1. Generate 16-byte random salt\n2. Derive AES key via Argon2id (15 iterations, 64MB)\n3. Generate 12-byte random IV\n4. Encrypt with AES-256-GCM\n5. Return Base64-encoded \n---\n \nDecrypts a  using the same password material.\nUsed for: Unwrapping the DEK from a KEK.\n  If the  is wrong, AES-GCM will throw an  (authentication tag mismatch). This is caught and presented as \"Incorrect Master Password\" in the UI.\n---\n \nGenerates a cryptographically random 256-bit Data Encryption Key.\nCalled once during vault initialization. The DEK lives for the lifetime of the vault.\n---\n \nEncrypts data directly with the raw DEK (no KDF step). This is the fast path used for encrypting actual vault data.\nUsed for: Encrypting individual credential passwords and the full vault blob.\nPerformance difference:\n Method  KDF?  Time per operation \n---------\n   Argon2id (15 iter, 64MB)  500ms \n   None (raw key import)  1ms \n---\n \nDecrypts data encrypted with the DEK.\nUsed for: Decrypting individual credential passwords for display and autofill.\n Data Types\n SealedPackage\nThe universal encryption output format:\n WrappedVaultPayload\nThe complete encrypted package stored on Walrus:\n Security Properties\n Property  Guarantee \n------\n Forward secrecy  Each encryption uses a fresh random IV and salt \n Key separation  DEK (data) and KEK (key wrapping) serve different purposes \n Authentication  GCM mode provides integrity checking — tampered ciphertext is rejected \n Brute-force resistance  Argon2id with 64MB memory makes each PIN guess take 500ms \n No key reuse  DEK operations use unique IVs; KEK operations use unique salts \n CredentialManager\nThe  class () handles encryption of zkLogin credentials for persistent storage:\nThis ensures that the Google JWT and zkLogin proof data are never stored in plaintext — they are wrapped with the user's KEK and can only be recovered by entering the Master PIN."},{"id":"/extension/walrus","title":"Walrus Integration","description":"Decentralized storage integration — encrypted vault blob management on Walrus Protocol.","url":"/extension/walrus","content":"Walrus Integration\nOrion uses Walrus Protocol as its decentralized storage layer. All encrypted vault data is stored as content-addressed blobs on the Walrus network, ensuring data permanence and censorship resistance.\n Architecture\n Components\n walrus.ts — Low-Level Client\nHandles raw HTTP interactions with Walrus endpoints:\n WalrusAdapter — High-Level Operations\nProvides typed operations for the :\n Endpoints\n Endpoint  URL  Purpose \n---------\n Publisher    Upload blobs \n Aggregator    Download blobs \n Response Format\nWalrus returns different response shapes depending on whether the blob is new or already exists:\nThe  function handles both cases transparently, always returning a  string.\n Data Flow\n Upload (Sync)\n1. Vault data is encrypted with DEK → \n2. DEK is wrapped with KEK → \n3. Recovery DEK is preserved → \n4. All three are bundled into \n5. JSON-serialized and uploaded as a binary blob\n6. Walrus returns a content-addressed \n7.  is stored on-chain via \n Download (Unlock/Recovery)\n1.  is read from Sui\n2. The blob is fetched from the Walrus Aggregator\n3. Parsed into \n4.  is decrypted with KEK → DEK\n5.  is decrypted with DEK → vault data\n  Walrus storage is content-addressed — the same encrypted payload always produces the same . If nothing changed, the upload is a no-op ( response)."}]}